Visualising coralseed outputs

2024-04-17

coralseed includes a function map_coralseed() that is a wrapper around other functions and tmap/leaflet to produce pretty interactive maps.

map_output <- map_coralseed(seed_particles=particles, settle_particles=settlers, 
              seascape_probability=seascape, restoration.plot=c(100,100)) 

map_output

to speed up coralseed and produce smaller files, set show.tracks = FALSE to omit the full set of particle tracks from the plots.



The main outputs from coralseed for plotting are:

# extract settlement points and paths
settlers <- settle_particles(particles, probability="additive", silent=TRUE)

# extract density, count, spatial area
settler_density <-settlement_density(settlers)


For example, the map below uses: a) the output of settle_particles() to extract the settlement points and dispersal paths prior to settlement, b) the output of settler_density() to create a minimal concave hull around the settled points to calculate a spatial footprint in m2 (here 5152m2, or half a hectare):

settler_density$area <- settler_density$area |> mutate(area=paste0(prettyNum(area, big.mark = ",")))

tmap1 <- tm_basemap("Esri.WorldTopoMap") + 
  tm_shape(settlers$paths, name="Particle tracks") +
    tm_lines(lwd=0.4, col="darkgrey") +
  tm_shape(settlers$points, name="Particle points") +
    tm_dots(col="dispersaltime", palette="Spectral", style = "cont", id="Dispersal time")

tmap2 <- tm_basemap("Esri.WorldTopoMap") + 
  tm_shape(settler_density$area, name="Spatial footprint") +
    tm_text("area", size=0.8, col = "black") +
    tm_fill(lwd=0.1, col="aquamarine3", alpha=0.5, legend.show=TRUE) +
    tm_borders(lwd=0.1, col="black", alpha=0.6) +
  tm_shape(settlers$points, name="Particle points") +
    tm_dots(col="black", id="Dispersal time", alpha=0.4)
  

tmap_arrange(tmap1, tmap2, ncol=2, widths = c(.5, .5), sync=TRUE)



1. base R

coralseed is slow (particularly loading dynamic maps) due to the size of the data produced, and leaflet files are large (upwards of 100mb).

To speed things up with large datasets, coralseed includes two static plotting functions in base r to quickly visualise outputs: plot_particles and plot_settlers() that can be used as follows:

Plot settlers:

settlers <-  settle_particles(particles, probability="additive", silent=TRUE)

plot_settlers(input=settlers, seascape=seascape)

Plot particles:

library(coralseed)

seascape <- seascape_probability(reefoutline=reef_map, habitat=benthic_map)

particles <- seed_particles(example="mermaid", seascape=seascape,
                            competency.function = "exponential",
                            limit.time=6, simulate.mortality = "typeI", 
                            simulate.mortality.n = 0.1, probability="additive",
                            silent=TRUE, return.plot=FALSE)

plot_particles(input=particles, seascape=seascape)

2. tmap/leaflet

tmap isn’t that well documented but is very effective as a front-end to leaflet when using sf and raster outputs. map_coralseed() is a wrapper around several functions that extract sf outputs from seed_particles() / settle_particles() and maps (type map_coralseed to see code).The output of these functions can be used to create simple dynamic tmap outputs, for example:

    library(tmap)
    library(tmaptools)

    tmap_mode("view")
    tm_shape(seascape, name = "habitats") +
      tm_fill("class", name = "Benthic habitats", alpha = 0.6) +    
    tm_shape(settlers$points, is.master=TRUE, name="settlers") +
      tm_dots(col = "aquamarine3") +
    tm_basemap(server="http://tile.stamen.com/terrain/{z}/{x}/{y}.png")

3. ggplot()

The results from coralseed can be used directly with ggplot2() and sf via geom_sf and coord_sf() for simple plotting:

    library(ggplot2)

    # crop seascape to the boundary of the settled larvae, add 100m spatial buffer
    subset_seascape <- st_crop(seascape, st_buffer(settlers$points, 100))
    
    ggplot() + theme_bw() +
      geom_sf(data=subset_seascape, aes(fill=class), alpha=0.2) +
      geom_sf(data=settlers$points, type=21, size=0.3, alpha=0.5)



Note the spatial outputs of coralseed use a projected coordinate system (EPSG:20353) which is specific to the east coast of Australia (AGD84 / AMG zone 53 between 132°E and 138°E). If plotting with other maps and data you may need convert coralseed` outputs to unprojected coordinates (e.g. EPSG:4326).
